                  Sir Philip Sydney 3. when hee had expressed the heauie departure of Dorus from his friend Pirocles, endeth thus; 
So much his owne heart did finde him faultie, to vnbend anie way the continuall vse of their deare friendship.
                  5. When he had manifested the inconstancie of the people, and setled perseuerance of Philanax & Euarchus, he addeth; 
So euil ballanced be the extremities of popular mindes, and so much naturall imperiousnes there rests in a wel framed spirit.

This is the Prosopopoeia of Peleus, which is thus left off;




